{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_016AnD7mno5jT6VdhwnDuqMP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HsgpWMjCW6wgiYdddqoW3U","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The orchestration layer collects data from three internal sources (metrics endpoint, issue tracker API, deployment log) and passes all retrieved data to the narrative summary generation step.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Unit-level mocking could hide real schema mismatches or data transformation bugs between the real API contracts and the expected models. The real failure boundary is: 'Can we reliably collect and combine data from all three sources given their real schemas and behavior?' A Unit test with generic mocks would always pass if the application correctly passes through whatever data it receives, but would miss cases where the real API returns unexpected structures that break the transformation logic. Integration-level testing with fixture-based mocks that reflect realistic source contracts will catch schema drift and transformation errors.","test_description":"Create test doubles for the three data sources using realistic response schemas. Verify that the orchestration layer calls all three sources, receives their data, and passes a combined dataset (containing all three source values) to the summarizer. Assert that omitting any source results in test failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior 1 establishes the happy-path data collection, which Behavior 2 (graceful degradation) and Behavior 3 (summarization) depend on. Behavior 4 (end-to-end) integrates this as the first step.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When any one of the three data sources is unavailable or fails, the report is produced with a 'data unavailable' note for that section, and the process does not abort.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The behavior is about deterministic exception handling within the application boundary: 'if a source fails, gracefully degrade and include a note.' Mocking a source to raise an exception is sufficient to test this logic—the application's response is deterministic regardless of whether the underlying cause is a network timeout, 404, or 500. Unit-level testing with mocked failures will catch the happy path of graceful degradation. The small risk that real failure modes (connection refusal, timeout duration, partial responses) behave subtly differently suggests some probability on Integration level, but the core testable behavior is at Unit level.","test_description":"Mock each of the three data sources separately to raise an exception (e.g., network error, timeout exception). For each case, verify that: (a) the orchestration catches the exception, (b) the process continues and collects from the other two sources, and (c) the final report includes 'data unavailable' in the section for the failed source.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior 2 is the degradation case for Behavior 1's happy path. It ensures robustness without requiring real external services.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary generated by the LLM accurately represents and includes the key values and metrics present in the input data without omission or material misrepresentation.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The correctness of the summary depends on what the real LLM produces, not on the application's plumbing. Mocking the LLM at Unit level tests 'if the LLM returns this summary, does the app include it?' but not 'does the LLM actually summarize correctly?' The real failure is: 'The LLM produces a summary that loses, misrepresents, or significantly reorders key data values.' This can only be caught by testing with a real LLM, which produces non-deterministic but qualitatively correctness-dependent output. Multiple runs with the same input may produce slightly different summaries; a real test must accept this variance while asserting that key values are always represented.","test_description":"Prepare structured input data with 3–5 explicitly known key values (e.g., 'deploy count: 7', 'error rate: 0.05%', 'mean latency: 1.2s'). Call the real LLM summarization endpoint with this data. Verify that the generated summary includes these values (or semantically equivalent descriptions) within tolerance for natural language variation. Run multiple times to confirm consistency.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior 3 depends on data correctly collected in Behavior 1 (and gracefully degraded in Behavior 2). It is a core quality gate for the report output.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report—from data collection through narrative generation through email delivery—completes end-to-end and the email successfully reaches the configured recipient's inbox.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"'Reaches the inbox' is a claim about real email infrastructure behavior. Mocking the email service (Unit level) would always succeed, missing real failure modes: SMTP server rejection, authentication failure, rate limiting, provider delivery delays, or filtering into spam. A test SMTP server (Integration level) can verify transmission to the server but may not catch provider-specific delivery, spam-filtering, or inbox routing issues. The real failure we want to catch is: 'Does the email actually arrive in the recipient's inbox?' This requires real email infrastructure or a close integration-level simulation with an actual email provider's test endpoints.","test_description":"Set up real or test-environment infrastructure for the three data sources (live or mocked), LLM API, and email service (using a real provider's test endpoint or staging SMTP). Execute the complete scheduled script once. Verify that: (a) the recipient's configured email address receives the message, (b) the email contains the expected report content, and (c) the email arrived within an acceptable time window.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior 4 is the end-to-end happy-path test that integrates Behaviors 1 (data collection), 3 (summarization quality), and validates the entire pipeline including Behavior 5's fallback.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable or fails during sending, the generated report is persisted to a local file, and the failure is recorded such that the next scheduled invocation of the script attempts to re-deliver the saved report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Unit-level testing can verify the immediate fallback: 'on email failure, save to file.' However, 'delivery is retried on the next scheduled run' requires testing state persistence and the retry cycle across two invocations of the script. The real failure boundary is: 'Does the system reliably save failed reports and re-attempt delivery on the next run without losing data?' This requires Integration-level infrastructure to manage file state, simulate or directly test consecutive runs, and verify the retry mechanism. We do not need System-level real email service behavior because the fallback and retry logic itself is deterministic; we are testing state management, not email reliability.","test_description":"Mock the email service to fail (e.g., raise connection timeout). Verify that: (a) the report is saved to a file with a recognizable name or format, and (b) a failure state is recorded. Then simulate the next scheduled run by either restarting the script or directly invoking the retry logic. Verify that the script loads the saved report from the file and attempts to re-deliver it.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Behavior 5 is the resilience/fallback case for Behavior 4's happy path. Together, they ensure the system does not lose reports under failure conditions.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13468,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13468},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34aea529-4662-4c40-a0a7-8e82d151709e","uuid":"a6745bcd-f2d5-48b1-81aa-f407173ace2d"}
